  "body": "### Description\n\nAs today the name of the `container` that the Kubernetes generates matches the name of the `artifactId` or the value of `quarkus.kubernetes.name` if that's set however the same value is used to set i.e. the name of the generated deployment resources.\r\n\r\nIn essence it behave as:\r\n\r\n```yaml\r\napiVersion: \"apps/v1\"\r\nkind: \"Deployment\"\r\nmetadata:\r\n  name: ${quarkus.kubernetes.name}\r\nspec:\r\n  template:\r\n    spec:\r\n      containers:\r\n      - image: \"foo/bar:latest\"\r\n        name: ${quarkus.kubernetes.name}\r\n```\r\n\r\nBut in some cases, it is needed to set a specific name to a container and as today that's only possible by post by post processing the generated kubernetes resource yaml.\r\n\n\n### Implementation ideas\n\n\r\nA new property, like `quarkus.kubernetes.container-name` can be introduced to allow users to set the name of the container.\r\nFor backward compatibility, the default of the new property could be  `${quarkus.kubernetes.name}` \r\n\r\n\r\n```yaml\r\napiVersion: \"apps/v1\"\r\nkind: \"Deployment\"\r\nmetadata:\r\n  name: ${quarkus.kubernetes.name}\r\nspec:\r\n  template:\r\n    spec:\r\n      containers:\r\n      - image: \"foo/bar:latest\"\r\n        name: ${quarkus.kubernetes.container-name}\r\n```",
